<DOC><DOCNO> AP880328-0271 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-28-88 2118EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-InsiderTrading     03-28 0255</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Insider Trading,0265</SECOND><HEAD>Trader in ``Yuppie 5'' Insider Ring Settles SEC Charges</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former stock analyst who pleaded guilty to acriminal charge in the ``Yuppie Five'' insider trading scandal,settled a civil action with the Securities and Exchange CommissionMonday.   Andrew Solomon, formerly a researcher at the Marcus Schloss andamp;Co. brokerage, settled civil charges by admitting his participationin a scheme to trade on inside information of corporate activities.   Insider trading is the wrongful use of confidential informationto profit in securities transactions.   The settlement is subject to a judge's approval.   Solomon, 28, of Manhattan, pleaded guilty June 5, 1986, to onecount of conspiracy. He was sentenced Nov. 26, 1986, to one year'sprobation, 250 hours of community service and a $10,000 fine.   He could have been sentenced to five years in prison and a$250,000 fine.   Solomon was part of a ring that included four Wall Streetprofessionals and one of their clients, all known as the ``YuppieFive.'' They traded in securities involved in six proposed oranticipated corporate takeovers using non-public information.   In settling the SEC civil charges, Solomon admitted passing oninside information about GAF Corp.'s tender offer for Union CarbideCorp., Dominion Textile's tender offer for Avondale Mills as wellas a takeover bid of American Brands by BAT Industries, all beforethey were made public.   In February, Marcus Schloss andamp; Co. agreed to pay $410,700 _without admitting or denying guilt _ to settle civil insidertrading charges with the SEC.</TEXT></DOC>